# Noita eye room cypher (Capybar\#6875) {#noita-eye-room-cypher-(capybar#6875)}

Starting off, I'm not a cryptographer of any kind, but I am a programmer and do know some maths so I decided to give it a try with a friend of mine (shoutout to Sopek\#5157 for showing me this puzzle and for lots of ideas and help\!).  
So far I've got to some conclusions, but it's hard to tell if any of them are particularly useful.

My research and data is highly connected to [this document](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1s6gxrc1iLJ78iFfqC2d4qpB9_r_c5U5KwoHVYFFrjy0/edit?usp=sharing) (I’ll refer to it as the ‘*Eye doc*’). If you haven’t seen it yet, you probably should.

Also, I just decided to make my code repository public \- if you know C\# and want to play around with the data, feel free to use it at [github](https://github.com/Doctor-Ned/NoitaEyeGlyphResearch)\!

***Update: I decided to reformat the doc and change it from ‘a documentation of a solution I’m testing’ to some kind of a ‘journal’ with each episode being a new idea, as I’ve gone over so many of them it’s pointless to talk of one of the ideas as superior.***  
***Therefore, please keep in mind that the most recent episode is the one that’s most likely to be useful, as I’ve moved on from the older ones for some reason.***

# Episode 1\. Initial doubts and index of coincidence {#episode-1.-initial-doubts-and-index-of-coincidence}

* Although the trigram model seems to be the best one to read in, I'm concerned about the order of the eyes, especially for the even trigrams. So my research includes different combinations of the eyes. Although the main focus was tod check the changes in even trigrams, I tested all 36 permutations. To make it easier I denoted trigram transformations into letter permutations (ABC) so that ABC ABC would mean the following (thought to be correct) read order:  
  ![][image1]  
  ***A message from the future: I decided against reordering the trigrams. Check episode 3\. for details.***  
* The messages may or may not be a standard text cypher. If it’s not anything like that, my research is *probably* pointless and meaningless.  
* Discord user trainowns\#6260 suggested testing [Index of Coincidence](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Index_of_coincidence): I decided to find out some more about that approach and implement it.

## Index of coincidence (*Ic*) {#index-of-coincidence-(ic)}

I am not going to get into details of what it is and how it works, but what matters is that when fed with messages and alphabets (deduced from the messages actually \- **this seems good, but might be an invalid approach and a modification might be considered**) it can determine the probability of two letters of different texts being the same. Knowing that, it’s easier to deduce a potential cyphering method and hence can help decipher the message.

* What might also be important is that for each language there’s a range of *Ic* values that is usually covered, so there’s also a possibility that specific *Ic* can be a hint of the coded language itself (although I do not think that is the case here). For example *Ic* for english language is about 0.0667, 0.0699 for finnish.  
* Low *Ic* might mean a wide alphabet being used or a polygraphic cypher. **It can also mean that the message is some gibberish that can’t be decrypted using this method**.  
* The *Ic* value is not bound to the actual representation of the character, so if we manage to decrypt the (thought to be\!) polygraphically cyphered message into decyphered trigrams, the resulting *Ic* can hopefully match a language (english or finnish, I guess). Sadly, in an extreme scenario the underlying language might not even be anything like that.

Now, if the eye messages are an encrypted text and my approach is valid, the cypher seems to be polygraphic. That means that the key is simply another, shorter text.

By checking autocoincidence (which is done by testing a message against itself, but split into a fixed number of columns equal to the potential key length) for some expected key lengths, we can now make a chart that quite literally might show us how likely the key is to be of given length. Basically a peak in the chart **might** mean we hit the spot. What is also worth noting is that there usually exists a peak for every multiple of the actual key length (so if the key consists of 5 characters, we should see a peak in the chart for 5, 10, 15 etc.).

çAnd so, having considered the alphabet of 83 unique trigrams (as described in *Eye doc*) I have plotted the *Ic* values over separate messages (in different trigram combinations, ofc.).  
**You need to keep in mind the most important part: I’m operating on TEXT consisting of TRIGRAMS, not actual latin characters. This means that for now I’m treating the message as being written in some kind of ‘metalanguage’ (it doesn’t affect the *Ic*\!) although I hope that each trigram can later be somehow mapped to a character.**

Also, obviously, I just chose SOME graphs out of many \- there’s a total of 36 transformations of odd+even trigrams.

**![][image2]**

**![][image3]**

**![][image4]**

At first glance the peaks are kinda random and it’s hard to notice any patterns. But here comes the real deal: each of 9 eye messages has some sections in common with the others. This may indicate a number of things (most of which I may not be aware of), but what I think is important is that it probably means that the key is common for all messages. I doubt the messages are designed in such a way that despite of the common sections they’re decyphered differently.

If the messages do share a common key, why not make an average *Ic* for each key length out of all messages? By combining multiple messages we get more data for analysis, meaning we should get better results. So now I generated graphs for average values across all of the messages.

**As this is the most interesting part (or at least it is such for me), it brings a lot of doubts. I am NOT sure whether doing this average is a valid approach. I think it makes sense, but may be wrong \- mainly because I don’t know why the consequent peaks you’re going to see appear only after stacking all messages together. This might indicate that the keys are different for each message and for some reason the common part spikes up in the average but means nothing. But I am holding onto hopes that this indeed makes sense.**

![][image5]

![][image6]

![][image7]

You’ve just seen 3 random graphs out of 36\. Remember that we don’t really need 36 representations, only **one** of them is correct (or 6, if you count transpositions) but I’m testing all of them just to widen my approach.

What matters is that **all** graphs share one common property: 2 visible peaks at 14 and 28 (which happens to be a multiple of 14). This indicates that there’s a **high** probability that if the text is polygraphically cyphered the key is 14 characters long. So what now?

## Oncoming steps {#oncoming-steps}

This is not the end of my work, as I’m still fighting to solve it. Remember that all of the above work means (pretty much) nothing if I made a serious mistake somewhere on the way (which is **very** possible) or if this is just not the way to solve this puzzle. But if it is…

* The key has a high probability of being 14 characters long. You can’t bruteforce that as there’s 5^14 possible options (over 6 billion\!).  
  So the point is to *somehow* find the key, but this search is split into two. We either seek for a string of 14 trigrams (or anything that can be their equivalent) **OR** for a 14-letter keyword and a way to translate it into trigrams (basically a 3 digit base 5 number). The second way seems more intuitive. If it turns out to be the proper approach, it immediately allows to translate the decoded trigrams back into actual text.  
* The method of translating trigrams into characters and back is hard to find (not to mention that it is not necessarily the proper approach at all\!). Each trigram codes a number in range 0-124 (doesn’t use all of that range, too), which is barely half a byte. One might consider standard text encodings: ASCII (which uses half a byte\!) or UTF8 (which utilizes a full byte **but** does support i.e. *finnish* characters which might be important). But how do we translate the trigram numbers into characters? There’s a lot of shifts and other operations one can choose but there’s literally no way to select a one that’s “better” over the others (although choosing ASCII and shifting by 32 seems reasonable as the values immediately cover the text-character range of the ASCII table).  
  Another thing is that our number interpretation of the eyes might be just **wrong**. 5 eye positions are mapped to numbers 0,1,2,3,4 respectively to the way the eyes are written in the game code. Hopefully this number mapping is correct, but **what if it is not**? The 5 eye graphics might really stand for anything. Not even necessarily numbers from 0 to 4\.  
* We need an alphabet\! Finnish? English? With or without separation into upper and lower case? The alphabet is extremely important as it usually affects the decryption itself. The only things I can think of right now are either one of standard character sets (as in different encodings like ASCII) **OR** the alphabet used by the red glyphs that are already in the game. I think there’s quite a chance this encryption method could share the alphabet with the red glyph one \- which might have been used by the devs as a hint for this riddle.  
    
* Personally, I haven’t ever played the game. I came here for the puzzle (though I’m pretty sure I’ll get the game and play it soon\!). What a friend of mine told me is that there’s that ever-present line in the game which goes:  
  **AS ABOVE, SO BELOW**  
  If you count the letters… Well, yeah, there’s 14\. So far that’s the only thing that might actually be a 14-character key and I’d love to think this is not a coincidence. Obviously there’s a huuge (pretty much infinite) amount of ways we can translate text into 3 digitsdigit, base 5 characters and back, and the key itself can be written in a number of ways. ALLUPPERCASE? alllowercase? OrMaybePascalCase? There’s 2^14 combinations (over 16k) but if that’s the key, I bet it’s one of the three above.  
  So far I have tried numerous ways of converting text into trigrams and trigrams into text, and none of them worked.

# A little change of thoughts {#a-little-change-of-thoughts}

So… The diamond cypher got me nowhere and I guess at this moment I recalled something I *shouldn’t have forgotten*. The analysis of all the eye messages revealed that while preserving the initially proposed trigram reading order and interpretation (3-digit base5 numbers) they cover the whole range of 000 to 313 (or 0 to 82 in base10). Getting such a contiguous value set looks so good that I think it’s **very** unlikely to be a coincidence. Therefore, I decided that reordering the trigrams is undesirable. And also, if we’re to hold onto this particular representation of the trigrams, diamond cypher is also **totally wrong** as it completely omits the order of the eyes with trigrams.

***Currently, the only thing from the previous episodes that I think does matter is the potential use of Index of coincidence.***

# Episode 3\. “Random bullshit go” {#episode-3.-“random-bullshit-go”}

At this point I started testing a lot of different ways, most of which seemed too random or chaotic to be possible. But it simply doesn’t hurt trying \- and with the codebase I currently prepared it was fairly easy to code more and more weird ways of processing the messages in little to no time. I see no point in describing most of them, but there are some which produce interesting results that \- although they don’t mean much by themselves \- I found potentially valuable and believe they could hint some properties of the messages that could be important for deducing a proper way of solving this goddamn puzzle.

## Episode 3.1. “The poem(-ish) way” {#episode-3.1.-“the-poem(-ish)-way”}

Here’s something that was proposed by Sopek\#5157 and, although it seemed unlikely, turns out to be quite interesting. As the trigrams overall cover the whole range of 000 to 313 (base5, obviously\!) it also means that for the first digit being in the range of \[0;2\] *all* of the combinations of the other 2 digits are used. As they’re in base5, the total amount of described values is 25 (5^2) \- which seems perfect for our 25-character latin alphabet (I know it’s 26, but the i/j is often treated as the same letter just for the sake of encoding, eventually ending up with a 25 character set). So what if we used the first digit as a *line number* and translated the remaining 2 digits into characters? For each eye string, we’d get a 4-line message of some sort. Here’s what it looks like:

The result of this episode is just as stated before: **there’s a significant correlation between the order of instances of trigrams starting with the same digit across multiple messages**. This may be important and might be a good starting point for proposing new decoding methods. *It might as well be a result of something, not the cause of it*.  
Ah, and yes, I checked the index of coincidence \- it’s fairly similar for each message and within range \[0.0348;0.0417\]. The messages are short, though, so although the *Ic* value seems too low for finnish or english (0.06-0.07), this possibility cannot be entirely rejected.  
For now and for this episode \- that’s about it.

# Alternative approach {#alternative-approach}

* What if the eye message is not a text? I’ve been thinking it might as well be some binary data. It could be the content of some binary file (a document? an image?).  
  Or maybe some transcription of bits. Although this seems kinda **stupid** I consider this to be an option, and \- because it’s fairly simple to code \- I will probably test it, too.

# Important facts to be faced (although I don’t want to face them) {#important-facts-to-be-faced-(although-i-don’t-want-to-face-them)}

* Until this secret is solved, there’s simply **no way** to determine whether any of us has ever been close to solving it. All of my research might be just totally pointless and useless. And even if I’m heading in the right direction \- the smallest flaw in either my reasoning or the code can make the difference between solving the puzzle and just getting farther and farther away from the answer.  
* IS IT EVEN TEXT?  
* What I (and a lot of other people) do is putting a lot of maths and computer programming into a riddle that is in a video game. **Initially I did not think this could be a good approach**. I would bet this puzzle has to be solvable by hand, ‘on paper’, without the need to go deep into maths and scripting. But I eventually I do that. Mainly because it’s been so much time and so much effort from a lot of people \- that makes me think that maybe this eye glyph puzzle is not an ordinary one, probably the devs just wanted it to be “impossible” to solve without tons of research, scripting and trial and errors.
